(Read this caption) Being vulnerable isn’t easy, doing something outside your comfort zone isn’t either, and looking like a beginner at another style when you’re actually an advanced skater feels odd. But, as a professional dance teacher of 15 years I have been a student more than I have taught and I continue to feel all those things. I blank out, I mess up, and I look cringe at times. But, over time my confidence blossoms by consistently putting myself in uncomfortable positions. If you can, learn every style, learn from everyone, and laugh at yourself. The more you expand your limits the more shades of the rainbow you have to color with. You will have more variety in your freestyle! I hope YOU reading this gets the chance to take a @dance.skate workshop from me one day. It’s not easy getting started, but you have to get started to be great. And, it’s not even about being great, it’s about having a fun time! All is welcome and all is encouraged to partake! Class is a safe space to color outside the lines, get sloppy, and try new things. All love. 💜

2020 DanceSkate, just some of it, but established in 2019. Here’s some throwback videos with some awesome people! Many of you don’t know, I created this simply as a passion project, and it still is! For no money and unpaid, I simply wanted to give recognition to so many great skaters. Before there wasn’t many skate pages, so I would purposely shout out dope skaters and OGs from Atl, LA, Chicago, NY, London and all around the GLOBE putting them all on the map! Many didn’t know other skaters outside their own city and country, and that’s why DanceSkate blew up fast in 2020. We were all on our phones during quarantine and I was showing you some amazing talent outside your local skate scene! This was a page giving recognition and a voice to so many. We did soooo many TakeOvers. Look at this hashtag to see how many we did: #DanceSkateTakeOver.

I’m an Editor and Motion Graphics Editor for a living. So, I created all these clips you see here outside of my real job. I had a blast making these with so many aspiring skaters and friends.

Thank you to everyone who’s been involved from the beginning and having fun creating this passion with me!

Words of inspiration and encouragement for today! 🤗 I was saying a couple of things here: 1. Learn from everyone because it amplifies your personal flow. You might have done that move differently with someone else, but now you have another way of doing it from another teacher. I became a dance teacher when I was 19 out of highschool. When I moved to LA I quit teaching to be a student again! I wanted to absorb everything! I didn’t want a coloring box of 20 crayons, I wanted 200! The moment you stop learning is when you hit the ceiling. Any person, age or gender, be open to learning from others because it’s for your evolvement not theirs. 

2. I have to tag the OG and created of Roller Dance himself @richardhumphrey. The video was cut short, but what I was teaching was upper body grooves, and I was referencing how smooth and groovy Mr. Humphrey is. It’s common for us skaters to want to be explosive with our moves, but before doing that find the beat and just groove. Let the music move you instead of being over the music. I believe dance comes from the torso, not the arms and legs. So, find the heartbeat whether that’s just nodding or clapping to the music, and then grow on from there. 

Happy Hollidays! And… if you don’t celebrate the holidays remember… life is merely your own perception, not anyone else’s. So shake any negative thoughts, and rewrite what you want to experience and perceive today! It’s your reality. Much love to everyone. ❤️
